TI  - Optimal configuration of EV charging infrastructure: A hybrid simulation approach
AU  - Xie, W
AU  - Han, GX
AU  - Liu, YP
AU  - Huang, JW
AB  - With the development of the EV industry, charging and swapping modes are gradually being promoted worldwide. This paper presents a hybrid simulation model implemented in AnyLogic aimed at optimizing the configuration of charging stations, swapping stations, and combined charging and swapping stations. The model integrates discrete event simulation, agent-based simulation, and system dynamics. Firstly, a discrete event simulation model is built based on the operation processes of battery charging and swapping. Subsequently, agent-based simulation models are proposed to capture the decision-making processes of EV drivers regarding charging and swapping, followed by the adoption of a system dynamics simulation model to analyze the energy consumption dynamics at swapping stations. To maximize station profitability, the Optquest optimization module is employed to determine the optimal configuration of the charging station, the swapping station, and the combined charging and swapping station. Case study results demonstrate that constructing combined charging and swapping stations yields the optimal configuration, leading to a 77% reduction in average waiting time and a 24% increase in profit. Additionally, the study finds that constructing charging stations is more cost-effective when EV arrivals are low (50-125), whereas constructing swapping stations becomes more costeffective as EV arrivals range from 126 to 170. Beyond 170 EV arrivals, the most cost-effective strategy is to establish combined charging and swapping stations. The research outcomes contribute valuable insights for enhancing the design and operational strategies of EV infrastructure configurations.
