TI  - Integrated fuzzy system dynamics-fuzzy agent-based modeling of construction crew motivation and productivity
AU  - Kedir, NS
AU  - Fayek, AR
AB  - Construction labor productivity (CLP) plays a crucial role as a key performance indicator for the success of construction undertakings. Previous studies have shown that crew motivation and situational/contextual factors (e.g., congestion, safety) in the construction environment affect CLP. However, a research gap exists regarding methods for capturing dynamic causal relationships between factors affecting CLP and the emergent behaviour of agents (e.g., crew motivation) while addressing subjective uncertainty in CLP modeling and prediction. This paper presents a new hybrid modeling technique integrating fuzzy logic, system dynamics (SD), and agent-based modeling (ABM) that leverages the strengths of these techniques to provide an approach capable of capturing subjectivity, dynamic causal interactions, and emergent behavior for improved modeling. This research advances the state of the art in SD modeling in construction engineering and management by enabling the SD model to simultaneously capture subjective uncertainty and emergent behavior of agents, using hybridization of fuzzy logic, SD, and ABM to create the proposed FSD-FABM model. Research results indicate the FSD-FABM model incorporating adaptive neuro-fuzzy inference system can provide the highest predictive accuracy of CLP compared to other models tested, which used linear regression or Mamdani-or Takagi-Sugeno based fuzzy inference systems. Data from an industrial construction project in Alberta served as a case study to demonstrate the proposed technique. The proposed FSD-FABM can be applied to developing a decision support system for productivity improvement strategies in construction projects. It can also be used to predict project other metrics of performance metrics in different types of projects.
