AB  - The implementation process in construction phases involves numerous entities with intricate relationships, posing challenges in simulation model development. This study systematically applies the concept of digital twins to analyze the influencing factors of carbon emissions in construction processes and establishes the coupling relationships among construction machinery, personnel, environment, and carbon emissions. The research proposes a digital twin model and companion carbon spatial theory considering building carbon emissions. Building upon this theoretical model, a hybrid simulation modeling method integrating system dynamics, discrete event, and agent-based simulation is presented to establish a mixed simulation model of construction carbon emissions. The case study results indicate an error rate of 5.46 % for the simulation model, affirming its validity. The study finds significant carbon emissions from idle machinery during queuing, with a maximum value reaching 36.5 kgCO2. Through scenario optimization, an overall reduction of 17.03 kgCO2 was achieved compared to the original case scenario. However, focusing solely on a specific piece of construction equipment, such as maximizing emission reductions for dump trucks (30-ton trucks reducing emissions by 43.4 % compared to 15-ton trucks), may result in an overall increase in overall construction carbon emissions (5.73 % increase). This research presents a systematic conceptual model that guides the development of carbon emission simulation models for the construction process, enabling carbon emissions management and analysis of construction equipment from a holistic to an individual level.
