AB  - This study aims to evaluate the lithium-ion batteries (LIBs) recycling process as a part of the supply chain network and assess its long-term economic and environmental impacts. A novel hybrid analysis incorporating agent-based, system dynamics, and metallurgical process analysis has been used to provide microscopic and macroscopic analyses of the integrated recycling system, which consists of waste collection facilities, trans-portation, and a waste recycling plant. The intersection between the supply chain and metallurgical process disciplines signifies this study's multidisciplinary nature. Mass balance calculation method and metallurgical process simulation software have been used to model physical and hydrometallurgy processing of the LIB waste within the recycling plant, respectively. The impacts of different LIB compositions and waste collection rate scenarios on economic and environmental performances have been evaluated. The results of the hybrid simu-lation show that selecting the type of LIB recycling process or technology must incorporate a thorough cost -benefit analysis since the recycling process' incentive depends on LIB composition and amount, operating cost, energy consumption, and waste outputs. The operating cost and waste outputs analyses must also cover LIB waste collection and transportation activities. This study offers valuable insights for LIB manufacturers, recycling companies, and the government in designing infrastructure for the electric vehicle's ecosystem.
